blocks.name: df-uncf
blocks.content: Define the uncurry functor, which can be defined equationally using ` evalF ` . Strictly speaking, the third category argument is not needed, since the resulting functor is extensionally equal regardless, but it is used in the equational definition and is too much work to remove. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 13-Jan-2017.)

blocks.name: df-diag
blocks.content: Define the diagonal functor, which is the functor ` C --> ( D Func C ) ` whose object part is ` x e. C |-> ( y e. D |-> x ) ` . The value of the functor at an object ` x ` is the constant functor which maps all objects in ` D ` to ` x ` and all morphisms to ` 1 ( x ) ` . The morphism part is a natural transformation between these functors, which takes ` f : x --> y ` to the natural transformation with every component equal to ` f ` . (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 6-Jan-2017.)

blocks.name: curfpropd
blocks.content: If two categories have the same set of objects, morphisms, and compositions, then they curry the same functor to the same result. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 26-Jan-2017.)
blocks.origin:
thm curfpropd(class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, class c4, class c5, wff w0) {
  |- wi(w0, wceq(co(cop(c0, c1), ccurf, c2), co(cop(c3, c4), ccurf, c2)))
  -| wi(w0, wceq(cfv(chomf, c0), cfv(chomf, c3)))
  -| wi(w0, wceq(cfv(ccomf, c0), cfv(ccomf, c3)))
  -| wi(w0, wceq(cfv(chomf, c1), cfv(chomf, c4)))
  -| wi(w0, wceq(cfv(ccomf, c1), cfv(ccomf, c4)))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c0, ccat))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c3, ccat))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c1, ccat))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c4, ccat))

blocks.name: diagval
blocks.content: Define the diagonal functor, which is the functor ` C --> ( D Func C ) ` whose object part is ` x e. C |-> ( y e. D |-> x ) ` . We can define this equationally as the currying of the first projection functor, and by expressing it this way we get a quick proof of functoriality. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 6-Jan-2017.) (Revised by Mario Carneiro, 15-Jan-2017.)

  -| wi(w0, wcel(c2, ccat))
} = {
  syl5eq(c0, co(cop(c1, c2), ccurf, co(c1, c1stf, c2)), co(c1, cdiag, c2), w0)
  ovmpt2d(hs0, hs1, c1, cdiag, c2, co(cop(c1, c2), ccurf, co(c1, c1stf, c2)), ccat, ccat, co(cop(cv(hs0), cv(hs1)), ccurf, co(cv(hs0), c1stf, cv(hs1))), universe, w0)
  a1i(w0, wceq(cdiag, cmpo(hs0, hs1, ccat, ccat, co(cop(cv(hs0), cv(hs1)), ccurf, co(cv(hs0), c1stf, cv(hs1))))))
  df-diag(hs0, hs1)
  oveq12d(cop(cv(hs0), cv(hs1)), ccurf, co(cv(hs0), c1stf, cv(hs1)), cop(c1, c2), co(c1, c1stf, c2), wa(w0, wa(wceq(cv(hs0), c1), wceq(cv(hs1), c2))))
  opeq12d(cv(hs0), cv(hs1), c1, c2, wa(w0, wa(wceq(cv(hs0), c1), wceq(cv(hs1), c2))))
  oveq12d(cv(hs0), c1stf, cv(hs1), c1, c2, wa(w0, wa(wceq(cv(hs0), c1), wceq(cv(hs1), c2))))
  simprl(w0, wceq(cv(hs0), c1), wceq(cv(hs1), c2))
  simprr(w0, wceq(cv(hs0), c1), wceq(cv(hs1), c2))
  ovexd(cop(c1, c2), ccurf, co(c1, c1stf, c2), w0)
  diff.hs0.s(hs1)
  diff.hs0.c(c1)
  diff.hs0.c(c2)

blocks.name: diagcl
blocks.content: The diagonal functor is a functor from the base category to the functor category. Another way of saying this is that the constant functor ` ( y e. D |-> X ) ` is a construction that is natural in ` X ` (and covariant). (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 7-Jan-2017.) (Revised by Mario Carneiro, 15-Jan-2017.)

thm diagcl(class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, wff w0) {

  curfcl(co(cop(c1, c3), ccurf, co(c1, c1stf, c3)), c1, c2, c3, co(c1, c1stf, c3), c1, w0)
  eqid(co(cop(c1, c3), ccurf, co(c1, c1stf, c3)))

  eqid(co(c1, cxpc, c3))
  eqid(co(c1, c1stf, c3))
}
